 Investors appealing to the and Securities Exchange Commission not to limit their access to information about stock and sales purchases by corporate insiders are .
 A proposal SEC to ease reporting requirements for some company executives would undermine the as a stock - picking tool usefulness of information on insider trades . , individual investors and professional money managers contend
 They make the argument in letters about rule changes that , among other things , would exempt many middle - management executives from reporting trades in their own companies ' shares proposed this past summer to the agency .
 The changes proposed also allow executives to report exercises of options later and less often would .
 Many of the letters maintain that investor confidence and the markets already so stacked against the little guy has been so shaken that any decrease in information on insider - trading patterns prompt individuals to get out of stocks altogether might by the stock market 1987 crash -- -- .
 `` The SEC has paid obeisance to the ideal of a field level playing historically , Clyde McGregor S. of Winnetka , , Ill. '' wrote in one of the 92 letters the agency has received since the changes proposed Aug. 17 were .
 `` Apparently the commission really did not believe in this ideal . ''
 Currently , the rules . force to report within about a month after the transaction purchases and sales of their ' companies shares executives , directors and other corporate insiders
 But about 25 % of the insiders , late , file according to SEC figures . their reports
 The changes were proposed in an effort to streamline federal bureaucracy and boost compliance by the who really are calling the shots executives `` , '' said Brian Lane , special counsel at the SEC 's office of disclosure policy which the changes proposed , .
 , Mr. Lane said . Investors , money managers and corporate officials until today , had to comment on the proposals and the issue produced more mail than almost any other issue in memory has
 , The SEC will probably vote on the proposal early next year he said .
 Not those all who wrote oppose the changes .
 The Committee on Federal Regulation Securities of for the American Bar Association argues , '' . , for example in its letter lengthy to the SEC , that the proposed changes `` would substantially improve the { law } by conforming to contemporary business realities it more closely
 the investors who oppose the proposed changes object What to most is the effect they say the proposal have on their ability to spot telltale `` clusters '' of trading activity within a short of time period -- buying or selling by more one than or director officer would .
 According to some estimates , the rule changes cut insider filings by more than a third would .
 The 's SEC Mr. Lane . vehemently those estimates disputed
 , . he said The rules proposed also be tougher on the insiders still required to file reports would
 Companies be compelled to publish in annual statements proxy the names of insiders who fail to file on time reports would .
 Considered as a whole , Mr. Lane , said the filings required under the proposed rules be at least as effective if , not more so , for investors following transactions '' `` will .
 Many investors wrote asking to require to report immediately , not a month later their purchases and sales insiders the SEC .
 But . said Mr. Lane that while the SEC regulates who files , to when so do the law tells them
 Investors who want to change the required timing should write their representatives in Congress added he , .
 , he said The SEC would likely be amenable to legislation that required insiders to file transactions on a basis more timely .
