 Researchers at Plant Genetic in Belgium Systems N.V. said they have developed a for creating hybrid for a number of key crops plants genetic engineering technique .
 The researchers said they isolated a plant gene that prevents the production of pollen have .
 The gene thus can prevent a plant from fertilizing itself .
 Such so - called male - sterile plants then can be fertilized , by pollen from another strain of the plant thereby producing hybrid seed .
 The generation new of plants will . possess the '' high - production trait flourishing , , similar to that now seen in hybrid corn known as hybrid vigor ``
 `` , '' . Murray president of Delta & Pine Land Co. , a Southwide Inc. subsidiary that is one of the largest in the U.S. producers cotton seed Robinson , said The development could have a dramatic effect on farm production , especially cotton
 On a commercial scale , the sterilization of the pollen - producing male part has only been achieved in corn and sorghum feed grains .
 That because the , male , the tassel part and the , female , the ear are some distance apart on the corn plant 's .
 In a labor - intensive process , the companies seed , cut off making it male sterile . the tassels of each plant
 They . a row of male - fertile plants which the plants male - sterile then pollinate sow , nearby
 The hybrid first corn produced using this approach mechanical seeds were introduced in the 1930s . and they yielded as as much 20 % more corn than naturally pollinated plants
 The majority vast of the corn U.S. crop now is grown from hybrid seeds produced by seed companies .
 A technique similar is . almost to apply to other crops , such as cotton , soybeans and rice impossible
 The part male , , the of the plant anthers and the , female , the pistils of the plant same are within a fraction of an inch or even attached to each other .
 The in these plants anthers are difficult to clip off .
 In China , a of workers great number , are engaged in pulling using tweezers out the of rice plants male organs and one - third of rice produced in that country is grown from hybrid seeds .
 At Plant Genetic Systems , have researchers isolated a pollen - inhibiting that can be inserted in a plant to confer male sterility gene .
 Jan , Leemans research director , said . this gene was successfully introduced in oil - producing , rapeseed plants a major crop in Europe and Canada , using as a carrier a `` promoter gene '' developed by Robert Goldberg at the Angeles University of in California Los
 The gene sterilizing is expressed just the pollen is about to develop before and it deactivates the anthers of every flower in the plant .
 Mr. Leemans said this manipulation genetic does n't hurt the growth of that plant .
 The researchers also pulled a trick genetic engineering second off in order to get in large enough numbers to produce a commercial hybrid seed crop male - sterile plants .
 They attached a second , gene for herbicide resistance , to the pollen - inhibiting gene .
 Both genes are then inserted into a few plants greenhouse , which pollinated and allowed to mature and produce seed are then .
 The of heredity laws dictate that half of the plants springing from these seeds greenhouse - produced will be male sterile and herbicide resistant and half will be male fertile and herbicide susceptible .
 The of herbicide application would kill off the male - fertile plants , leaving a large field of male - sterile plants that can be cross - pollinated to produce hybrid seed .
 Mr. Leemans said the created with this genetic engineering hybrid rapeseeds yield 15 % % more to 30 than the commercial strains used currently output .
 `` This technique is applicable to a wide of crops variety , and added that some modifications may be necessary to accommodate the peculiarities of each type of crop '' he said . ,
 He said the company , experimenting on alfalfa with the technique is and plans to include cotton and corn among other crops , .
 He that even though virtually all corn seeds currently planted are hybrids , obviate the need for mechanical emasculation of anthers , which costs U.S. seed producers about $ 70 million annually the genetic approach will said .
 In recent years , spurred research at a number of chemical and biotechnology including Monsanto Co. , Shell Oil Co. and Eli Lilly & Co companies , has demand for hybrid seeds .
 One developed by some of these companies technique involves a chemical spray supposed to kill only a plant 's pollen .
 But have there been problems with chemical sprays damaging plants ' female reproductive organs and concern for the of such chemical sprays toxicity to humans , animals and beneficial insects .
 However , Paul Johanson , Monsanto 's director of plant sciences , . said '' the company 's chemical spray these problems overcomes and `` is gentle on the female organ
 Biosource Corp. Genetics , Vacaville Calif. , , is developing a spray containing a that to cell spreads from cell and interferes with the genes that are responsible for producing pollen gene .
 This , gene called `` gametocide , '' is carried into the plant by a virus that remains for a few days active .
 Robert , Erwin president of Biosource , called Plant Genetic 's approach . `` interesting '' and `` novel and `` complementary rather than competitive , '' ''
 `` There is a out there large market hungry for hybrid seeds , '' . he said
