 A conflict bitter with global implications has erupted between Nomura Securities Co. two of the world 's most powerful financial companies , and Industrial Japan Bank of .
 The clash is a of a new and divisiveness toughness in Japan 's circles once - cozy financial sign .
 Not only are Japan 's institutions financial putting their enormous clout to work ; they 're squaring against one another off in unprecedented public fashion increasingly .
 Already , the consequences being felt by other players in the financial markets even governments -- are .
 What triggered the latest clash was a skirmish over the timing of a bond New Zealand government issue .
 Nomura attempting to organize the 50 billion - yen ( $ ) 352 million borrowing at a time many Japanese banks , led by Industrial Bank Japan of , were when pressuring the Wellington government to help recover loans made to a bank defunct investment that had been owned by New 's Zealand civil - service pension fund them in Japan was .
 Unwilling to put up until those debts are repaid new money for New Zealand most banks refused , to even play administrative roles in the new financing , forcing an embarrassed Nomura to postpone it this week .
 The dispute shows clearly the power global of Japan 's financial titans .
 Aside from Nomura 's injured pride , the victim biggest so far . has been the New Zealand government
 Barred by its budget law from making any new domestic bond issues , been casting abroad to raise the 3 billion New Zealand dollars it to come up with by the of its fiscal year end next June 30 needs ( US$ 1.76 billion ) to NZ$ 4 billion Wellington 's Debt Management Office . had
 With Japan 's cash - flush banks aligned against it , though . be difficult , raising money may
 Not only they can block from raising in Japan money Wellington but as the underwriters largest in the Eurobond market , they might be able to scuttle borrowings there , too . , say bankers here ,
 New 's Zealand finance , minister David Caygill , lashed out at such suggestions .
 He in Wellington reporters told that the government had , n't guaranteed the loans to DFC , New Zealand Ltd. an investment bank 80% - owned by the National Provident Fund and would n't bail it out Tuesday .
 `` It may very well be what the banks Japanese want , . he Radio New Zealand told ''
 `` think I it be irresponsible would and I am not about to be blackmailed by Japanese banks or any other international interests . ''
 No significant less than the banks Japanese ' attempt to cut off funds to pressure a foreign government are the implications of a confrontation between Japan securities and banking industries .
 Anxiety rising over recent proposals government to eventually lower the strict that -- and protect -- now separate the two industries from each other barriers is .
 Both sides , are jealously their turf guarding . and relations have been for months at a flashpoint
 The banks badly want to break into all of the securities business aspects .
 Meanwhile , the securities most -- of them smaller than the banks -- companies are seeking access only limited kinds of banking that would n't open them to the full brunt of competition from the banks to .
 Nomura , the world 's largely by virtue of its protected home field biggest company securities , , and Industrial of Bank Japan , Japan 's most innovative and aggressive bank in capital markets abroad captain the opposing sides .
 And their suspicions of each other run deep .
 In the past year , have both tried to stretch the limits of their businesses .
 And Industrial Bank of Japan , up started a securities London subsidiary that Japanese stocks sells to non - Japanese overseas institutions a move that stirred the anger of the stock brokerage firms .
 The New Zealand bond issue has simply brought the two institutions face - face to - .
