 Some allies U.S. are complaining that President Bush pushing conventional - arms talks , too quickly creating a that negotiators will make errors that could affect the security of Western Europe for years risk is .
 Concerns about the pace of the Vienna talks -- which are aimed at the as well as major reductions and realignments of troops in central Europe destruction of some 100,000 weapons , -- are also . being registered at the Pentagon
 Mr. Bush has called for an agreement by next September at the latest .
 But some American defense officials believe the North Atlantic Treaty Organization should take more time to examine the long - term implications of the options being considered .
 For one thing , . worry that the U.S. have a much tougher time persuading Europeans to keep on their soil some short - range nuclear weapons once Soviet forces armored thinned out are will Pentagon , officials who asked not to be identified ,
 At the same time , contend they that a reduction of NATO forces under a treaty will increase the of a conventional Soviet attack possibility unless the West retains a residual force of nuclear weapons in Europe .
 Allies concerned about the deadline include the British French and smaller some of whom have adequate staffs to provide quick answers to the questions being raised by what generally are considered the arms - control most complex talks ever attempted do n't NATO allies , , .
 So far , no ally complained openly preserving the impression that NATO is in line with the position Bush that a quick agreement bringing Soviet conventional forces down to parity with NATO the West 's priority top bargaining is , has .
 But even though NATO negotiators have only 10 months left under the Bush timetable , they wrestling over such seemingly fundamental questions as `` What is a tank ? '' are still
 Five of the six of weapons categories under negotiation have n't even . been defined
 Tanks are currently defined as armored vehicles weighing 25 tons or more that carry large guns .
 The Soviets complicated the issue . by offering to include light tanks , which are as light as 10 tons
 Oleg Grinevsky A. , the Soviet chief negotiator in the conventional - arms talks , argued . that this mean the Soviets would have to destroy some 1,800 tanks , while the U.S. would lose none because it in Europe has no tanks light would
 But the issue is stickier than it seems .
 France Britain and Italy , have all light tanks they would like to keep out of the talks .
 And some U.S. Army analysts that the Soviet proposed redefinition is aimed at blocking the U.S. from developing lighter , more transportable , high - technology tanks worry .
 Defining combat aircraft is . even tougher
 The Soviets , insisted that aircraft brought into the talks be then . argued for exempting because they `` are solely defensive some 4,000 Russian planes ''
 NATO n't has budged from its insistence that any gun - carrying plane has offensive capability .
 The over that issue dispute , and only President Bush and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev may be able to resolve it , according to one U.S. official , is '' a treaty `` potential stopper .
 Accounting problems raise more issues knotty .
 Greece and Turkey , , for example are suspected of overstating their arsenals in hopes that they can emerge from the arms - reduction treaty with large remaining forces to deter each other .
 Other nations are n't sure how many weapons have they in their own arsenals .
 `` It 's just going to be sloppy , both on our side and theirs { } the Warsaw 's Pact , '' one NATO analyst says .
 So far , neither administration the Bush nor arms - control experts in Congress seem moved by arguments that these problems to thrash out may take more time than President Bush has allowed .
 They that the danger bigger would be that the West would delay action so long that the Soviets back away from the current conciliatory attitude might argue .
 `` So what if you miss 50 tanks somewhere ? '' asks Rep. Norman Dicks , ( ) D. , Wash. a member of the House group that visited the talks in Vienna .
 `` The bottom line that if we get that superiority { } Warsaw Pact brought down to parity can , we ought to keep pressing ahead as quickly as possible is .
 I more worry about things becoming so unraveled that they might become unable to negotiate on the other side .
