 Congressional and the administration Bush Democrats , agreed on a compromise minimum - wage bill . opening the way for the first wage - floor boost in more than nine years
 The agreement ended a between the leaders congressional and the White House long impasse over the wage issue .
 President Bush in June vetoed a measure passed by Congress and said he would n't accept any rise minimum - wage that went beyond limits he set early in this year 's debate on the issue .
 The compromise was a version somewhat softened of the White House had said it would what accept .
 Under the agreement with the House and Senate leaders , the minimum wage would . rise from the current 3.35 $ an hour to $ 4.25 an hour by April 1991
 Employers also could pay a '' subminimum training `` wage for 90 days , to new workers who are up 19 to years old and for another 90 days if the company institutes a specific training program for the newcomers then .
 White House officials were delighted that the compromise includes the concept of a training Mr. Bush fought for which throughout the year has wage , .
 `` For the first in history time , have we a training that will be part '' of the nation 's labor laws wage , said Roger Porter , assistant to the president for economic and domestic policy .
 White House aides said that although they made a small compromise on the length of a training wage , the final minimum - wage increase will meet the standards set by Mr. Bush .
 The vetoed by the president in June bill , the House failed to which override , would have lifted the minimum wage to $ 4.55 an hour by late 1991 with a training generally a worker 's first job for , wage for up to two months , .
 Mr. Bush had been holding for a boosting the wage floor to $ 4.25 an hour by the end of 1991 bill , coupled with a six - month wage training for workers newly hired by any employer out .
 Under the compromise , the $ 4.25 level be reached , nine months earlier unless it is tied to a training plan , while the training subminimum be shorter would would .
 Democrats that the wage training was a of allowing employers to pay while new workers need far less than six months to be trained for their jobs less than the minimum wage , way argued .
 Democrats been negotiating on a compromise with some Republican congressional leaders lately had .
 With congressional elections next year , GOP leaders worried about opposing a rise minimum - wage for low - paid workers at a time Congress is when moving toward a capital - gains tax cut that would directly wealthier taxpayers benefit have .
 Republicans been imploring the House White to compromise on the wage issue have .
 In the Senate , Edward Kennedy ( D. Mass. , ) chairman , and Pete Domenici ( R. , N.M . ) ranking minority of the Budget Committee member , of the Labor Committee , , . have been working on a compromise , and , a official Democratic staff said their soundings that the Senate appeared to be heading toward enough to override another Bush veto strength showed
 The House is scheduled to vote this week on the compromise , as a substitute to a new , bill Democratic itself watered down from last spring 's version .
 The Senate will probably vote not long afterward .
 Some Democrats thought they have compromised too much might .
 Rep. Murphy Austin ( Pa. D. , ) chairman , of the labor standards House subcommittee , they have done better `` if we 'd held their feet to the fire might said . ''
 Mr. Kennedy suggested Democrats '' `` a great deal yielded on the size of the increase , but he concessions from the White House on the training wage , he said which make it `` less harsh cited . ''
 , . he said With only 16 - year - olds to 19 - year - olds eligible , wo 68 % of workers getting less than $ 4.25 an hour , who are adults , n't be subject to the training wage
