 Mr. Stoll draws his title from the cuckoo 's habit of laying making them surrogate parents eggs in the nests of other birds , .
 The spy computer had discovered that a popular editing / electronic mail program called Gnu - Emacs do with the widely used Unix operating system created by AT&T tricks could .
 Using Gnu - Emacs , the spy could substitute a bogus program `` atrun '' for the one that cleans routinely up the Unix system every five minutes .
 Once his cuckoo 's egg laid was , could he enter Unix and become a `` '' , super - user with access to everything .
 Mr. Stoll was scanning when ran his grant low and he was asked to switch to helping run the lab 's computers the heavens in 1986 at the observatory Keck of the Laboratory Lawrence Berkeley .
 He discovered a 75 - cent discrepancy in the charges made to various departments for computer time and traced to a user named `` Hunter , '' who had no valid billing address it .
 Mr. Stoll suspected the intruder one of those precocious students who has fun breaking into computers was .
 But after much tracking , . , it , became evident that the hacker not was on the Berkeley campus or even in California through various clues to Mr. Stoll
 Finding him became an obsession for Mr. Stoll .
 He made a midnight of all the printers he could lay hands on requisition so that he could monitor all the telephone lines coming into the lab 's computers .
 After discovering that the hacker taken over the dormant account of a legitimate user named Joe Sventek had , rigged he up an alarm system , including a portable beeper to alert him when Sventek came on the line , .
 Some nights he slept under his desk .
 His boss complained about neglect of other chores .
 The hacker was pawing also but using Berkeley and other computers easily accessible as stepping to the network of computers used by the military and national security agencies stones over the Berkeley files .
 The White Sands missile and CIA contractor Mitre Inc. range among the targets . were
 When the hacker moved , , Mr. Stoll moved too calling up but keeping his own system open to avoid arousing suspicion other systems managers to alert them .
 Sometimes if the hacker to be into a sensitive file seemed , , he would . drag across the terminal his keychain to create static or slow the system down to frustrate his quarry
 The FBI initially , showed little interest and he had the impression other federal security agencies were tangled in legal red tape up .
 One learns a lot about crippling federal bureaucracy from this book , . , or seems to
 `` Seems to '' it 's possible that the CIA and the National Security Agency more than they let on to Mr. Stoll interested were because .
 Finally he help got , .
